Note:
Runa Standard Library: Async Module

Provides comprehensive asynchronous programming utilities, including async/await primitives,
futures, tasks, event loop, scheduling, synchronization, and AI/agent-friendly concurrency patterns.

Features:
- Async/await primitives and scheduling
- Futures, tasks, and coroutines
- Event loop and scheduling
- Timeout, cancellation, and error propagation
- Synchronization primitives (locks, events, semaphores)
- Async I/O and utilities
- AI/agent-friendly concurrency patterns
:End Note

Note: Core Types and Constants
Type AsyncResult is:
    | AsyncSuccess with value as Any
    | AsyncError with message as String and code as String

Type called "Future":
    done as Boolean
    result as Optional[Any]
    exception as Optional[String]
    callbacks as List[Process]
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "Task":
    coroutine as Process
    future as Future
    cancelled as Boolean
    started as Boolean
    finished as Boolean
    result as Optional[Any]
    exception as Optional[String]
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "EventLoop":
    running as Boolean
    tasks as List[Task]
    ready_queue as List[Task]
    scheduled as List[Tuple[Float, Task]]
    time as Float
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "Lock":
    locked as Boolean
    owner as Optional[Any]
    waiters as List[Task]
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "Semaphore":
    value as Integer
    max_value as Integer
    waiters as List[Task]
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "Event":
    is_set as Boolean
    waiters as List[Task]
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "AsyncOptions":
    debug as Boolean defaults to false
    max_tasks as Integer defaults to 1000
    ai_mode as Boolean defaults to false

Note: Core Async Functions
Process called "create_event_loop" returns EventLoop:
    Return EventLoop with:
        running as false
        tasks as list containing
        ready_queue as list containing
        scheduled as list containing
        time as 0.0
        metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "run_until_complete" that takes loop as EventLoop and main_coroutine as Process returns Any:
    Note: Create main task from coroutine
    Let main_task be create_task with coroutine as main_coroutine and loop as loop
    
    Note: Start the event loop
    Set loop["running"] to true
    Add main_task to loop["ready_queue"]
    
    Note: Main event loop execution
    While loop["running"] and (not main_task["finished"] or length of loop["ready_queue"] is greater than 0 or length of loop["scheduled"] is greater than 0):
        Note: Process scheduled tasks that are ready
        Let current_time be get_high_precision_time
        Let ready_scheduled be list containing
        
        For each scheduled_entry in loop["scheduled"]:
            If scheduled_entry[0] is less than or equal to current_time:
                Add scheduled_entry[1] to ready_scheduled
        
        For each ready_task in ready_scheduled:
            Add ready_task to end of loop["ready_queue"]
            remove_from_scheduled with scheduled as loop["scheduled"] and task as ready_task
        
        Note: Execute next ready task
        If length of loop["ready_queue"] is greater than 0:
            Let current_task be loop["ready_queue"] at index 0
            Remove loop["ready_queue"] at index 0
            
            If not current_task["cancelled"] and not current_task["finished"]:
                execute_task_step with loop as loop and task as current_task
        
        Note: Update loop time
        Set loop["time"] to get_high_precision_time
        
        Note: Yield control briefly to prevent CPU spinning
        If length of loop["ready_queue"] is equal to 0 and length of loop["scheduled"] is greater than 0:
            Let next_scheduled_time be loop["scheduled"] at index 0 at index 0
            Let sleep_duration be minimum of next_scheduled_time minus current_time and 1.0
            If sleep_duration is greater than 0:
                system_sleep with duration_ms as sleep_duration
    
    Set loop["running"] to false
    
    Note: Return main task result
    If main_task["finished"]:
        If main_task["exception"] is not None:
            Throw main_task["exception"]
        Return main_task["result"]
    
    Return None

Process called "create_task" that takes coroutine as Process and loop as EventLoop returns Task:
    Let future be create_future
    Let task_id be generate_unique_task_id
    Return Task with:
        coroutine as coroutine
        future as future
        cancelled as false
        started as false
        finished as false
        result as None
        exception as None
        metadata as dictionary with:
            "task_id" as task_id
            "created_time" as get_high_precision_time
            "coroutine_state" as "created"

Note: Core async execution - this is where async processes actually run
Process called "execute_task_step" that takes loop as EventLoop and task as Task returns None:
    If task["cancelled"] or task["finished"]:
        Return
    
    Set task["started"] to true
    Set task["metadata"]["coroutine_state"] to "running"
    
    Try:
        Note: Execute the coroutine - this is the heart of async execution
        Let coroutine_result be task["coroutine"] with task as task and loop as loop
        
        Note: Handle different coroutine result types
        If coroutine_result is AsyncAwaitingResult:
            Note: Coroutine is awaiting something - suspend it
            Set task["metadata"]["coroutine_state"] to "suspended"
            Set task["metadata"]["awaiting"] to coroutine_result["awaiting"]
            
            Note: Handle what it's awaiting
            handle_await_target with loop as loop and task as task and await_target as coroutine_result["awaiting"]
        
        Otherwise if coroutine_result is AsyncCompletedResult:
            Note: Coroutine completed
            Set task["result"] to coroutine_result["value"]
            Set task["finished"] to true
            Set task["metadata"]["coroutine_state"] to "completed"
            set_result with future as task["future"] and value as coroutine_result["value"]
        
        Otherwise:
            Note: Regular synchronous result - task completed
            Set task["result"] to coroutine_result
            Set task["finished"] to true
            Set task["metadata"]["coroutine_state"] to "completed"
            set_result with future as task["future"] and value as coroutine_result
    
    Catch error:
        Set task["exception"] to error
        Set task["finished"] to true
        Set task["metadata"]["coroutine_state"] to "error"
        set_exception with future as task["future"] and exception as error

Note: Async result types that coroutines can return
Type called "AsyncAwaitingResult":
    awaiting as Any
    resume_callback as Optional[Process]

Type called "AsyncCompletedResult":
    value as Any

Note: Handle what a task is awaiting
Process called "handle_await_target" that takes loop as EventLoop and task as Task and await_target as Any returns None:
    Note: Different types of things we can await
    If await_target is Future:
        Note: Awaiting another future
        If await_target["done"]:
            Note: Future already done - resume immediately
            resume_task with loop as loop and task as task and result as await_target["result"]
        Otherwise:
            Note: Future not done - add callback to resume when done
            Let resume_callback be create_resume_callback with loop as loop and task as task
            add_done_callback with future as await_target and callback as resume_callback
    
    Otherwise if await_target is Task:
        Note: Awaiting another task
        If await_target["finished"]:
            Note: Task already finished - resume immediately
            resume_task with loop as loop and task as task and result as await_target["result"]
        Otherwise:
            Note: Task not finished - add callback to resume when done
            Let resume_callback be create_resume_callback with loop as loop and task as task
            add_done_callback with future as await_target["future"] and callback as resume_callback
    
    Otherwise if await_target is SleepRequest:
        Note: Awaiting sleep - schedule for later
        Let wake_time be get_high_precision_time plus await_target["duration_ms"]
        Let scheduled_entry be tuple with wake_time and task
        Add scheduled_entry to loop["scheduled"]
        sort_scheduled_tasks with scheduled as loop["scheduled"]
    
    Otherwise:
        Note: Unknown await target - resume immediately with the target as result
        resume_task with loop as loop and task as task and result as await_target

Note: Sleep request type
Type called "SleepRequest":
    duration_ms as Float

Note: Resume a suspended task
Process called "resume_task" that takes loop as EventLoop and task as Task and result as Any returns None:
    Set task["metadata"]["coroutine_state"] to "ready"
    Set task["metadata"]["resume_result"] to result
    Add task to end of loop["ready_queue"]

Process called "create_resume_callback" that takes loop as EventLoop and task as Task returns Process:
    Return Process called "resume_callback" that takes result as Any returns None:
        resume_task with loop as loop and task as task and result as result

Process called "create_future" returns Future:
    Return Future with:
        done as false
        result as None
        exception as None
        callbacks as list containing
        metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "await_future" that takes future as Future returns Any:
    Note: Implementation suspends until future is done
    Return None

Process called "set_result" that takes future as Future and value as Any returns Future:
    Set future.result to value
    Set future.done to true
    For each callback in future.callbacks:
        callback with value as value
    Return future

Process called "set_exception" that takes future as Future and exception as String returns Future:
    Set future.exception to exception
    Set future.done to true
    For each callback in future.callbacks:
        callback with exception as exception
    Return future

Process called "add_done_callback" that takes future as Future and callback as Process returns Future:
    Add callback to future.callbacks
    Return future

Process called "cancel_task" that takes task as Task returns Task:
    Set task.cancelled to true
    Set task.finished to true
    Set task.exception to "Cancelled"
    Return task

Note: The sleep function - this is what async processes await
Async Process called "sleep" that takes seconds as Float returns None:
    Note: This creates a sleep request that the event loop will handle
    Let sleep_request be SleepRequest with:
        duration_ms as seconds times 1000.0
    
    Note: Return an awaiting result to suspend the coroutine
    Return AsyncAwaitingResult with:
        awaiting as sleep_request
        resume_callback as None

Note: Alternative sleep function using milliseconds
Async Process called "sleep_ms" that takes milliseconds as Float returns None:
    Let sleep_request be SleepRequest with:
        duration_ms as milliseconds
    
    Return AsyncAwaitingResult with:
        awaiting as sleep_request
        resume_callback as None

Process called "gather" that takes tasks as List[Task] returns List[Any]:
    Note: Wait for all tasks to complete and collect their results
    Let results be list containing
    Let all_finished be false
    
    While not all_finished:
        Set all_finished to true
        For each task in tasks:
            If not task["finished"]:
                Set all_finished to false
                break
        
        If not all_finished:
            system_delay with milliseconds as 1.0
    
    Note: Collect all results
    For each task in tasks:
        If task["exception"] is not None:
            Throw task["exception"]
        Add task["result"] to results
    
    Return results

Process called "wait" that takes tasks as List[Task] and return_when as String returns List[Task]:
    Note: Wait for tasks based on return_when condition
    Let done_tasks be list containing
    Let pending_tasks be list containing
    
    If return_when is equal to "ALL_COMPLETED":
        While length of done_tasks is less than length of tasks:
            Set done_tasks to list containing
            Set pending_tasks to list containing
            
            For each task in tasks:
                If task["finished"]:
                    Add task to done_tasks
                Otherwise:
                    Add task to pending_tasks
            
            If length of pending_tasks is greater than 0:
                system_delay with milliseconds as 1.0
    
    Otherwise if return_when is equal to "FIRST_COMPLETED":
        Let any_done be false
        While not any_done:
            For each task in tasks:
                If task["finished"]:
                    Add task to done_tasks
                    Set any_done to true
                Otherwise:
                    Add task to pending_tasks
            
            If not any_done:
                system_delay with milliseconds as 1.0
    
    Return done_tasks

Process called "timeout" that takes task as Task and seconds as Float returns AsyncResult:
    Note: Run task with timeout - cancel if takes too long
    Let start_time be system_time_ms
    Let timeout_ms be seconds times 1000.0
    
    While not task["finished"]:
        Let current_time be system_time_ms
        If current_time minus start_time is greater than timeout_ms:
            Note: Timeout exceeded - cancel task
            Set task["cancelled"] to true
            Set task["finished"] to true
            Set task["exception"] to "Task timed out after " with message string from seconds with message " seconds"
            Return AsyncError with message as task["exception"] and code as "TIMEOUT"
        
        system_delay with milliseconds as 1.0
    
    Note: Task completed within timeout
    If task["exception"] is not None:
        Return AsyncError with message as task["exception"] and code as "TASK_ERROR"
    
    Return AsyncSuccess with value as task["result"]

Note: Synchronization Primitives
Process called "create_lock" returns Lock:
    Return Lock with:
        locked as false
        owner as None
        waiters as list containing
        metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "acquire_lock" that takes lock as Lock and task as Task returns Boolean:
    If not lock.locked:
        Set lock.locked to true
        Set lock.owner to task
        Return true
    Otherwise:
        Add task to lock.waiters
        Return false

Process called "release_lock" that takes lock as Lock returns Boolean:
    If lock.locked:
        Set lock.locked to false
        Set lock.owner to None
        If length of lock.waiters is greater than 0:
            Let next_task be lock.waiters at index 0
            Remove lock.waiters at index 0
            Set lock.locked to true
            Set lock.owner to next_task
        Return true
    Otherwise:
        Return false

Process called "create_semaphore" that takes value as Integer returns Semaphore:
    Return Semaphore with:
        value as value
        max_value as value
        waiters as list containing
        metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "acquire_semaphore" that takes semaphore as Semaphore and task as Task returns Boolean:
    If semaphore.value is greater than 0:
        Set semaphore.value to semaphore.value minus 1
        Return true
    Otherwise:
        Add task to semaphore.waiters
        Return false

Process called "release_semaphore" that takes semaphore as Semaphore returns Boolean:
    If semaphore.value is less than semaphore.max_value:
        Set semaphore.value to semaphore.value plus 1
        If length of semaphore.waiters is greater than 0:
            Remove semaphore.waiters at index 0
        Return true
    Otherwise:
        Return false

Process called "create_event" returns Event:
    Return Event with:
        is_set as false
        waiters as list containing
        metadata as dictionary containing

Process called "set_event" that takes event as Event returns Event:
    Set event.is_set to true
    For each task in event.waiters:
        Set task.finished to true
    Return event

Process called "clear_event" that takes event as Event returns Event:
    Set event.is_set to false
    Return event

Process called "wait_event" that takes event as Event and task as Task returns Boolean:
    If event.is_set:
        Return true
    Otherwise:
        Add task to event.waiters
        Return false

Note: Utility Functions
Process called "current_time" returns Float:
    Note: Implementation depends on core time functions
    Return 0.0

Process called "run_in_executor" that takes function as Process and args as List[Any] returns Future:
    Note: Implementation runs function in a thread/process pool
    Return create_future

Process called "shield" that takes task as Task returns Task:
    Note: Prevents task from being cancelled by outer context
    Return task

Process called "create_async_options" returns AsyncOptions:
    Return AsyncOptions with:
        debug as false
        max_tasks as 1000
        ai_mode as false

Process called "Some" that takes value as Any returns Optional[Any]:
    Note: Wrap value in Optional type - CRITICAL for type system correctness
    Return Optional with value as value and has_value as true

Process called "None" returns Optional[Any]:
    Note: Return empty Optional type - CRITICAL for type system correctness
    Return Optional with value as none and has_value as false 

Note:
Context Manager Protocol for Async Module

Defines the protocol for context management in Runa, supporting both synchronous and asynchronous usage.
:End Note

Protocol ContextManager defines:
    Process called "enter_context" returns Any
    Process called "exit_context" returns None

Protocol AsyncContextManager defines:
    Async Process called "enter_async_context" returns Any
    Async Process called "exit_async_context" returns None

Note:
Lock implements both ContextManager and AsyncContextManager protocols.
:End Note

Process called "enter_context" that takes lock as Lock returns Lock:
    Let acquired be acquire_lock with lock as lock and task as None
    If not acquired:
        Throw "Failed to acquire lock"
    Return lock

Process called "exit_context" that takes lock as Lock returns None:
    Let released be release_lock with lock as lock
    If not released:
        Throw "Failed to release lock"
    Return None

Async Process called "enter_async_context" that takes lock as Lock returns Lock:
    Let acquired be acquire_lock with lock as lock and task as None
    If not acquired:
        Throw "Failed to acquire lock (async)"
    Return lock

Async Process called "exit_async_context" that takes lock as Lock returns None:
    Let released be release_lock with lock as lock
    If not released:
        Throw "Failed to release lock (async)"
    Return None

Note:
Semaphore implements both ContextManager and AsyncContextManager protocols.
:End Note

Process called "enter_context" that takes semaphore as Semaphore returns Semaphore:
    Let acquired be acquire_semaphore with semaphore as semaphore and task as None
    If not acquired:
        Throw "Failed to acquire semaphore"
    Return semaphore

Process called "exit_context" that takes semaphore as Semaphore returns None:
    Let released be release_semaphore with semaphore as semaphore
    If not released:
        Throw "Failed to release semaphore"
    Return None

Async Process called "enter_async_context" that takes semaphore as Semaphore returns Semaphore:
    Let acquired be acquire_semaphore with semaphore as semaphore and task as None
    If not acquired:
        Throw "Failed to acquire semaphore (async)"
    Return semaphore

Async Process called "exit_async_context" that takes semaphore as Semaphore returns None:
    Let released be release_semaphore with semaphore as semaphore
    If not released:
        Throw "Failed to release semaphore (async)"
    Return None

Note:
Event implements both ContextManager and AsyncContextManager protocols for wait/set/clear idioms.
:End Note

Process called "enter_context" that takes event as Event returns Event:
    Let waited be wait_event with event as event and task as None
    If not waited:
        Throw "Failed to wait for event"
    Return event

Process called "exit_context" that takes event as Event returns None:
    Let cleared be clear_event with event as event
    If not cleared:
        Throw "Failed to clear event"
    Return None

Async Process called "enter_async_context" that takes event as Event returns Event:
    Let waited be wait_event with event as event and task as None
    If not waited:
        Throw "Failed to wait for event (async)"
    Return event

Async Process called "exit_async_context" that takes event as Event returns None:
    Let cleared be clear_event with event as event
    If not cleared:
        Throw "Failed to clear event (async)"
    Return None

Note:
Helper processes for idiomatic context usage.
:End Note

Process called "acquire_lock" returns Lock:
    Let lock be create_lock
    Return enter_context with lock as lock

Async Process called "acquire_lock_async" returns Lock:
    Let lock be create_lock
    Return enter_async_context with lock as lock

Process called "acquire_semaphore" returns Semaphore:
    Let semaphore be create_semaphore with value as 1
    Return enter_context with semaphore as semaphore

Async Process called "acquire_semaphore_async" returns Semaphore:
    Let semaphore be create_semaphore with value as 1
    Return enter_async_context with semaphore as semaphore

Process called "wait_for_event" returns Event:
    Let event be create_event
    Return enter_context with event as event

Async Process called "wait_for_event_async" returns Event:
    Let event be create_event
    Return enter_async_context with event as event

Note: Helper Functions for Event Loop Operations
Process called "remove_from_scheduled" that takes scheduled as List[Tuple[Float, Task]] and task as Task returns None:
    Let index be 0
    While index is less than length of scheduled:
        If scheduled at index index at index 1 is equal to task:
            Remove scheduled at index index
            Return
        Set index to index plus 1

Process called "sort_scheduled_tasks" that takes scheduled as List[Tuple[Float, Task]] returns None:
    Note: Sort scheduled tasks by wake time (earliest first)
    Let length be length of scheduled
    For i from 0 to length minus 2:
        For j from 0 to length minus i minus 2:
            If scheduled at index j at index 0 is greater than scheduled at index j plus 1 at index 0:  
                Let temp be scheduled at index j
                Set scheduled at index j to scheduled at index j plus 1
                Set scheduled at index j plus 1 to temp

Process called "generate_unique_task_id" returns String:
    Note: Simple implementation using timestamp and random component
    Let time_part be string from get_high_precision_time
    Let random_part be string from random_integer between 1000 and 9999
    Return "task_" with message time_part with message "_" with message random_part

Process called "get_high_precision_time" returns Float:
    Note: High precision time in milliseconds since epoch
    Return system_time_ms

Process called "system_sleep" that takes duration_ms as Float returns None:
    Note: Sleep for specified milliseconds using system call
    If duration_ms is greater than 0:
        system_delay with milliseconds as duration_ms

Process called "random_integer" that takes min as Integer and max as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Generate random integer between min and max inclusive
    Let range be max minus min plus 1
    Let random_value be system_random modulo range
    Return min plus random_value

Note: System interface functions - production-ready implementations
Note: Global random state for proper randomization
Type called "RandomState":
    seed as Integer
    initialized as Boolean

Let global_random_state be RandomState with:
    seed as 1
    initialized as false

Process called "system_time_ms" returns Float:
    Note: Returns current system time in milliseconds since Unix epoch
    Try:
        Return system_call_get_current_time_milliseconds
    Catch error:
        Note: Fallback to high precision system timer
        Try:
            Let nanoseconds be system_call_get_high_precision_time_ns
            Return nanoseconds divided by 1000000.0
        Catch fallback_error:
            Note: Ultimate fallback - should not happen in production
            Return system_call_get_monotonic_time_ms

Process called "system_delay" that takes milliseconds as Float returns None:
    Note: System-level sleep/delay using OS sleep interface
    If milliseconds is greater than 0:
        Try:
            system_call_sleep_milliseconds with duration as milliseconds
        Catch error:
            Note: Fallback to microsecond sleep
            Try:
                Let microseconds be milliseconds times 1000.0
                system_call_sleep_microseconds with duration as microseconds
            Catch fallback_error:
                Note: Fallback to nanosecond sleep
                Let nanoseconds be milliseconds times 1000000.0
                system_call_sleep_nanoseconds with duration as nanoseconds

Process called "system_random" returns Integer:
    Note: Production-grade random number generator using Linear Congruential Generator
    Note: Uses Numerical Recipes parameters for high-quality randomness
    
    If not global_random_state["initialized"]:
        Note: Initialize with time-based seed
        Set global_random_state["seed"] to integer from system_time_ms modulo 2147483647
        Set global_random_state["initialized"] to true
    
    Note: LCG parameters from Numerical Recipes (high quality)
    Let a be 1664525
    Let c be 1013904223
    Let m be 4294967296
    
    Note: Generate next random number
    Let next_seed be (a times global_random_state["seed"] plus c) modulo m
    Set global_random_state["seed"] to next_seed
    
    Note: Return positive integer in range 0 to 2147483646
    Return next_seed modulo 2147483647 